{"title_page": "Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=June 2008}}\n\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)\n| cover      = Sly-fam-thankyou-star.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Sly and the Family Stone]]\n| album      = [[Greatest Hits (Sly and the Family Stone album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| A-side     = [[Everybody Is a Star]]\n| released   = December 1969\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = 1969\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Funk]]\n| length     = 4:48\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Sly Stone]]\n| producer   = Sly Stone\n| prev_title = [[Hot Fun in the Summertime]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| title      =\n| title2     = [[Everybody Is a Star]]\n| next_title = [[Family Affair (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Family Affair]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|NOa5UOHdwnc|\"Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)\" (audio)}}}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Slyfam-thankyou-1969.ogg\n | description = \"Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)\"\"\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)'''\" is a 1969 song recorded by [[Sly and the Family Stone]]. The song, released as a [[A-side and B-side#Double A-side|double A-side]] single with \"[[Everybody Is a Star]]\", reached number one on the soul single charts for five weeks, and reached number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in February 1970.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942\u20132004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=534}}</ref> ''Billboard'' ranked the record as the No. 19 song of 1970.<ref>[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1970]]</ref>\n\n\"Thank You\" was intended to be included on an in-progress album with \"Star\" and \"[[Hot Fun in the Summertime]]\"; but the LP was never completed, and the three tracks were instead included on the band's 1970 ''[[Greatest Hits (Sly and the Family Stone album)|Greatest Hits]]'' LP. \"Thank You\" and \"Star\", the final Family Stone recordings issued in the 1960s, marked the beginning of a 20-month gap of releases from the band, which would finally end with the release of \"[[Family Affair (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Family Affair]]\" in 1971.\n\nThe song's length on the original hit single and the ''Greatest Hits'' LP is 4:48 and was [[Duophonic|re-channeled to simulate stereo]] on the popular ''Greatest Hits'' LP. The previously unreleased full-length version (6:18) was mixed by Bob Irwin in true stereo and its only issue was on a 1990 Columbia promotional CD ''Legacy: Music for the Next Generation''. On the subsequent (and currently available as of 2015) ''The Essential Sly & The Family Stone'' 2-CD set, the track is in stereo but is the standard 4:48 length hit version.\n\nThe song was ranked number 402 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's \"[[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\".\n\n==Song information==\n\n===Overview===\nThe title is an intentional [[mondegreen]] or [[sensational spelling]] for \"thank you for letting me be myself again.\" The third verse contains specific references to the group's previous successful songs, \"[[Dance to the Music (song)|Dance to the Music]]\", \"[[Everyday People (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Everyday People]]\", \"[[Sing a Simple Song]]\", and \"[[You Can Make It If You Try]]\". The song features co-lead vocals from [[Sly Stone]], [[Rose Stone]], [[Freddie Stone]], [[Cynthia Robinson]], [[Jerry Martini]], [[Greg Errico]] and [[Larry Graham]].\n\n===Cover versions===\n*A slower arrangement of the song (retitled \"Thank You for Talkin' to Me Africa\") is the closing track of the band's next album, ''[[There's a Riot Goin' On]]'' (1971).\n\n*In 1970, pianist [[Junior Mance]] included an instrumental cover of the song on his album, ''[[With a Lotta Help from My Friends]]''.<ref>[http://www.jazzdisco.org/atlantic-records/catalog-1500-series/#sd-1562 Atlantic Records Catalog: 1500 Series] accessed April 19, 2016</ref>\n\n*[[Maceo Parker|Maceo & All the King's Men]] covered the song on their 1970 album ''Doing Their Own Thing''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maceo Parker / Maceo & All the King's Men Doin' Their Own Thing|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/doin-their-own-thing-mw0000245289|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> \n\n*[[Gladys Knight and the Pips]] did a cover version of the song in 1971.{{fact|date=April 2017}}\n\n*[[Magazine (band)|Magazine]] covered the song in 1980 on the album ''[[The Correct Use of Soap]]''. The same recording was issued as the A-side of a single, and a live version was included on the 1981 album ''Play''.{{fact|date=April 2017}}\n\n*[[Soundgarden]] performed it on their 1989 tour and during their [[John Peel]] session that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilstu.edu/~mareede/sglg89.html|title=Soundgarden Live Guide|accessdate=2008-08-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041011125527/http://www.ilstu.edu/~mareede/sglg89.html|archivedate=2004-10-11}}</ref>\n\n*[[Dave Matthews Band]] has performed this song for many years, typically in the second set<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmbalmanac.com/TourSongShows.aspx?sid=257&tid=98&where=2008|title=DMBAlmanac.com|accessdate=2008-08-14}}</ref>\n\n*[[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Eddie Murphy]] covered the song for the credits of the 2007 animated film ''[[Shrek the Third]]'', and its [[List of songs featured in Shrek#Shrek the Third|soundtrack]].\n\n*[[Widespread Panic]] includes portions of this song during live performances as [[John Bell (musician)|John Bell]] \"raps\", most commonly during \"Barstools and Dreamers\" and \"Red Hot Mama Girl\".\n \n*[[Lonnie Smith (jazz musician)|Lonnie Smith]] performed the song on May 21, 1970 at Club Mozambique in Detroit.  A [[Live at Club Mozambique (Lonnie Smith album)|recording of this concert]] was released in 1995.\n\n*[[My Morning Jacket]] performed the song as a medley with Janet Jackson's \"Rhythm Nation\" on New Year's Eve 2017, at 1st Bank Center in Denver, Colorado.\n\n* [[Dr. John]] included the song on his 1994 studio album ''[[Television (Dr. John album)|Television]]''.\n\n* [[Big Brovaz]] performed a cover of the song for the 2004 film ''[[Scooby-Doo 2: Monsters Unleashed]]'', which is also included on the soundtrack album.\n\n* Jazz singer [[Eddie Jefferson]] did a version on his 1996 album ''Vocal Ease''.\n\n===In other media===\n[[Janet Jackson]]'s 1989 song \"[[Rhythm Nation]]\" samples the groove from the song in between verses.<ref>{{Citation|title=Rhythm Nation|date=2020-02-27|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Rhythm_Nation&oldid=942872999|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIt is featured in the video game [[Skate 2]].\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Sly Stone]] \u2013 co-[[lead vocals]], [[guitar]], writer, producer\n* [[Rose Stone]] \u2013 co-lead vocals\n* [[Jerry Martini]] \u2013 [[tenor saxophone]] and co-lead vocals\n* [[Cynthia Robinson]] \u2013 [[trumpet]] and co-lead vocals\n* [[Freddie Stone]] \u2013 guitar, co-lead vocals\n* [[Larry Graham]] \u2013 [[Bass (guitar)|bass]], co-lead vocals\n* [[Greg Errico]] \u2013 [[drums]] and co-lead vocals\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 1970|List of ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one singles of 1970]]\n*[[List of number-one R&B singles of 1970 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|sly-the-family-stone|thank-you-falettinme-be-mice-elf-agin}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Sly and the Family Stone}}\n\n[[Category:Sly and the Family Stone songs]]\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:1970 singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Sly Stone]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sly Stone]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=June 2008}}\n\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)\n| cover      = Sly-fam-thankyou-star.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Sly and the Family Stone]]\n| album      = [[Greatest Hits (Sly and the Family Stone album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| A-side     = [[Everybody Is a Star]]\n| released   = December 1969\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = 1969\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Funk]]\n| length     = 4:48\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Sly Stone]]\n| producer   = Sly Stone\n| prev_title = [[Hot Fun in the Summertime]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| title      =\n| title2     = [[Everybody Is a Star]]\n| next_title = [[Family Affair (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Family Affair]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|NOa5UOHdwnc|\"Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)\" (audio)}}}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Slyfam-thankyou-1969.ogg\n | description = \"Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)\"\"\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)'''\" is a 1969 song recorded by [[Sly and the Family Stone]]. The song, released as a [[A-side and B-side#Double A-side|double A-side]] single with \"[[Everybody Is a Star]]\", reached number one on the soul single charts for five weeks, and reached number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in February 1970.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942\u20132004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=534}}</ref> ''Billboard'' ranked the record as the No. 19 song of 1970.<ref>[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1970]]</ref>\n\n\"Thank You\" was intended to be included on an in-progress album with \"Star\" and \"[[Hot Fun in the Summertime]]\"; but the LP was never completed, and the three tracks were instead included on the band's 1970 ''[[Greatest Hits (Sly and the Family Stone album)|Greatest Hits]]'' LP. \"Thank You\" and \"Star\", the final Family Stone recordings issued in the 1960s, marked the beginning of a 20-month gap of releases from the band, which would finally end with the release of \"[[Family Affair (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Family Affair]]\" in 1971.\n\nThe song's length on the original hit single and the ''Greatest Hits'' LP is 4:48 and was [[Duophonic|re-channeled to simulate stereo]] on the popular ''Greatest Hits'' LP. The previously unreleased full-length version (6:18) was mixed by Bob Irwin in true stereo and its only issue was on a 1990 Columbia promotional CD ''Legacy: Music for the Next Generation''. On the subsequent (and currently available as of 2015) ''The Essential Sly & The Family Stone'' 2-CD set, the track is in stereo but is the standard 4:48 length hit version.\n\nThe song was ranked number 402 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's \"[[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\".\n\n==Song information==\n\n===Overview===\nThe title is an intentional [[mondegreen]] or [[sensational spelling]] for \"thank you for letting me be myself again.\" The third verse contains specific references to the group's previous successful songs, \"[[Dance to the Music (song)|Dance to the Music]]\", \"[[Everyday People (Sly and the Family Stone song)|Everyday People]]\", \"[[Sing a Simple Song]]\", and \"[[You Can Make It If You Try]]\". The song features co-lead vocals from [[Sly Stone]], [[Rose Stone]], [[Freddie Stone]], [[Cynthia Robinson]], [[Jerry Martini]], [[Greg Errico]] and [[Larry Graham]].\n\n===Cover versions===\n*A slower arrangement of the song (retitled \"Thank You for Talkin' to Me Africa\") is the closing track of the band's next album, ''[[There's a Riot Goin' On]]'' (1971).\n\n*In 1970, pianist [[Junior Mance]] included an instrumental cover of the song on his album, ''[[With a Lotta Help from My Friends]]''.<ref>[http://www.jazzdisco.org/atlantic-records/catalog-1500-series/#sd-1562 Atlantic Records Catalog: 1500 Series] accessed April 19, 2016</ref>\n\n*[[Maceo Parker|Maceo & All the King's Men]] covered the song on their 1970 album ''Doing Their Own Thing''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maceo Parker / Maceo & All the King's Men Doin' Their Own Thing|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/doin-their-own-thing-mw0000245289|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> \n\n*[[Gladys Knight and the Pips]] did a cover version of the song in 1971.{{fact|date=April 2017}}\n\n*[[Magazine (band)|Magazine]] covered the song in 1980 on the album ''[[The Correct Use of Soap]]''. The same recording was issued as the A-side of a single, and a live version was included on the 1981 album ''Play''.{{fact|date=April 2017}}\n\n*[[Soundgarden]] performed it on their 1989 tour and during their [[John Peel]] session that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilstu.edu/~mareede/sglg89.html|title=Soundgarden Live Guide|accessdate=2008-08-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041011125527/http://www.ilstu.edu/~mareede/sglg89.html|archivedate=2004-10-11}}</ref>\n\n*[[Dave Matthews Band]] has performed this song for many years, typically in the second set<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmbalmanac.com/TourSongShows.aspx?sid=257&tid=98&where=2008|title=DMBAlmanac.com|accessdate=2008-08-14}}</ref>\n\n*[[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Eddie Murphy]] covered the song for the credits of the 2007 animated film ''[[Shrek the Third]]'', and its [[List of songs featured in Shrek#Shrek the Third|soundtrack]].\n\n*[[Widespread Panic]] includes portions of this song during live performances as [[John Bell (musician)|John Bell]] \"raps\", most commonly during \"Barstools and Dreamers\" and \"Red Hot Mama Girl\".\n \n*[[Lonnie Smith (jazz musician)|Lonnie Smith]] performed the song on May 21, 1970 at Club Mozambique in Detroit.  A [[Live at Club Mozambique (Lonnie Smith album)|recording of this concert]] was released in 1995.\n\n*[[My Morning Jacket]] performed the song as a medley with Janet Jackson's \"Rhythm Nation\" on New Year's Eve 2017, at 1st Bank Center in Denver, Colorado.\n\n* [[Dr. John]] included the song on his 1994 studio album ''[[Television (Dr. John album)|Television]]''.\n\n* [[Big Brovaz]] performed a cover of the song for the 2004 film ''[[Scooby-Doo 2: Monsters Unleashed]]'', which is also included on the soundtrack album.\n\n* Jazz singer [[Eddie Jefferson]] did a version on his 1996 album ''Vocal Ease''.\n\n===In other media===\n[[Janet Jackson]]'s 1989 song \"[[Rhythm Nation]]\" samples the groove from the song in between verses.{{cn|date=January 2018}}\n\nIt is featured in the video game [[Skate 2]].\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Sly Stone]] \u2013 co-[[lead vocals]], [[guitar]], writer, producer\n* [[Rose Stone]] \u2013 co-lead vocals\n* [[Jerry Martini]] \u2013 [[tenor saxophone]] and co-lead vocals\n* [[Cynthia Robinson]] \u2013 [[trumpet]] and co-lead vocals\n* [[Freddie Stone]] \u2013 guitar, co-lead vocals\n* [[Larry Graham]] \u2013 [[Bass (guitar)|bass]], co-lead vocals\n* [[Greg Errico]] \u2013 [[drums]] and co-lead vocals\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 1970|List of ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one singles of 1970]]\n*[[List of number-one R&B singles of 1970 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|sly-the-family-stone|thank-you-falettinme-be-mice-elf-agin}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Sly and the Family Stone}}\n\n[[Category:Sly and the Family Stone songs]]\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:1970 singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Sly Stone]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sly Stone]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Pastcineo", "label": "safe", "comment": 