{"title_page": "Rudi Sk\u00e1cel", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Rudi (refugee) Sk\u00e1cel\n| image = Rudolf Sk\u00e1cel.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Sk\u00e1cel playing for Hearts in 2011\n| fullname = Rudolf Sk\u00e1cel\n| height = 1.78 m\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1979|7|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Trutnov]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| position = [[Attacking Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1985\u20131992\n| youthclubs1 = FK Trutnov\n| youthyears2 = 1992\u20131999\n| youthclubs2 = [[FC Hradec Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9|Hradec Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9]]\n| years1 = 1999\u20132002\n| clubs1 = [[FC Hradec Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9|Hradec Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9]]\n| caps1 = 37\n| goals1 = 8\n| years2 = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs2 = [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]]\n| caps2 = 57\n| goals2 = 13\n| years3 = 2003\u20132006\n| clubs3 = [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]\n| caps3 = 20\n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2004\u20132005\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 16\n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2005\u20132006\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Scumbos tv |Scumbos]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 35\n| goals5 = 16\n| years6 = 2006\u20132009\n| clubs6 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n| caps6 = 83\n| goals6 = 5\n| years7 = 2008\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Hertha BSC]] (loan)\n| caps7 = 16\n| goals7 = 2\n| years8 = 2009\n| clubs8 = [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]]\n| caps8 = 5\n| goals8 = 3\n| years9 = 2010\n| clubs9 = [[Larissa F.C.|Larissa]]\n| caps9 = 7\n| goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2010\u20132012\n| clubs10 = [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]\n| caps10 = 58\n| goals10 = 25\n| years11 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs11 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n| caps11 = 14\n| goals11 = 1\n| years12 = 2013\n| clubs12 = [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]]\n| caps12 = 5\n| goals12 = 0\n| years13 = 2015\u20132016\n| clubs13 = [[FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]]\n| caps13 = 2\n| goals13 = 0\n| years14 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs14 = [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n| caps14 = 24\n| goals14 = 0\n| years15 = 2017\u20132019\n| clubs15 = [[1. FK P\u0159\u00edbram]]\n| caps15 = 43\n| goals15 = 5\n| totalcaps = 422 | totalgoals = 80\n| nationalyears1 = 2001\u20132002\n| nationalteam1 = [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2003\u20132010\n| nationalteam2 = [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 7\n| nationalgoals2 = 1\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{medal|Country|{{fb|CZE}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2002 Switzerland]]|}}\n}}\n'''Rudolf Sk\u00e1cel''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8ska\u02d0ts\u025bl|lang}}; born 17 July 1979) is a retired professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played [[Midfielder|attacking midfielder]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edinburghlive.co.uk/sport/football/hearts-legend-rudi-skacel-calls-16369855|title=Hearts legend speaks on his decision to retire from football|last=Pilcher|first=Ross|date=3 June 2019|website=edinburghlive|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref> He was capped at international level by the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]]. He was generally deployed as a left sided [[midfield]] player but proved himself to be versatile, having also played as a central [[Midfielder#Attacking|attacking midfielder]] and a [[Left back#Full back|left back]] at Southampton.\n\nSk\u00e1cel began his career with [[FC Hradec Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9]] before joining [[Gambrinus liga]] side [[Slavia Prague]], where he caught the attention of [[France|French]] giants [[Olympique de Marseille]]. However, he struggled to establish himself in the first-team during his time with ''L'OM'' and was loaned out to [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] and [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]. The latter loan spell saw him establish himself as a fan favourite, culminating in him scoring in the [[2006 Scottish Cup Final]] as the ''Jambos'' emerged victorious. He then went on to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] where he spent three years, including a six-month loan spell with [[Hertha BSC]]. before being released. A brief return to [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]] and a short spell with [[AEL 1964 FC|Larissa]] followed, before he returned to Hearts. His second spell at the Edinburgh club proved to be just as successful as he ended both seasons as the club's top scorer and scored two goals in the [[2012 Scottish Cup Final]] against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]' biggest rivals [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] en route to another cup victory.\n\nHe has received infrequent call-ups to the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic national team]] squad, amassing seven caps over a period of seven years.\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Czech Republic===\nSk\u00e1cel was born in [[Trutnov]] and began his career with Czech club [[FC Hradec Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9]], making his senior debut in 1999 and helping his team to gain promotion back to the Czech top flight. In February 2002 he was signed by [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]], for a fee of 14 million [[Czech koruna]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/slavia-koupila-juniorskeho-reprezentanta-fjm-/fotbal.aspx?c=A020221_092030_fotbal_min|title=Slavia koupila juniorsk\u00e9ho reprezentanta|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|date=21 February 2002|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> In May 2002 he won the [[Czech Cup]] with Slavia, beating their fierce rivals [[Sparta Prague]] in the final. He also won gold with the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] in the [[European Under-21 Football Championship]].\n\nHis [[UEFA Cup]] and [[Gambrinus liga|Czech league]] performances in the 2002\u201303 season were noticed by [[France|French]] club [[Olympique de Marseille]] manager [[Alain Perrin]].\n\n===Marseille===\nIn August 2003 Marseille concluded a deal<ref>{{cite web | url = http://quickstart.clari.net/qs_se/webnews/wed/bq/Qfbl-fra-cze-skacel.R62-_DaV.html | title = Marseille sign Skacel | date = 31 August 2003 | publisher = clari.net | accessdate = 13 March 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071012120614/http://quickstart.clari.net/qs_se/webnews/wed/bq/Qfbl-fra-cze-skacel.R62-_DaV.html/ | archivedate = 12 October 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> to sign Sk\u00e1cel for a fee of 2.5 million Euros. He made his debut on 13 September 2003, playing the entire match in a 5\u20130 victory over [[Le Mans FC|Le Mans]] at [[Stade V\u00e9lodrome]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=103643&cc=5739 | title = Report: Marseille 5\u20130 Le Mans | publisher = ESPN Soccernet | date = 13 September 2003 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> His first and only goal for ''L'OM'' came in a 3\u20131 home victory over [[SC Bastia|Bastia]] on 5 October 2003.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/126071?cc=5739 | title = Report: Marseille 3\u20131 Bastia | publisher =  ESPN Soccernet| date = 5 October 2003 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter his first season at Marseille, Sk\u00e1cel found himself out of favour after [[Alain Perrin]] was sacked. This led to Sk\u00e1cel being loaned out to Greek club [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] with an option of a permanent deal. He scored twice on his debut in a 3\u20132 cup victory over [[Atsalenios F.C.|Atsalenios]]. Sk\u00e1cel played in the [[UEFA Champions League]] for the first time in his career for Panathinaikos, playing in five of the six group and scoring in a 2\u20132 away draw with [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] as the Greek club finished third in Group E to earn the consolation of a place in the [[UEFA Cup]]. During his time with Panathinaikos he scored five goals in all competitions.\n\n===Heart of Midlothian===\nAfter [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] did not take up their option to buy Sk\u00e1cel, [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] manager [[George Burley]] stepped in with an offer to take him on a season's loan from Marseille. In July 2005, the deal was concluded to take Sk\u00e1cel to Hearts on loan with the option of a permanent deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/heart_of_midlothian/4694147.stm |title=Hearts complete capture of Skacel |date=19 July 2005 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of the 2005\u201306 season, Hearts won the first seven league games with Sk\u00e1cel scoring in each of them to set a [[Scottish Premier League]] record. Sk\u00e1cel's home debut was a 4\u20130 victory over [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]' city rivals [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] at [[Tynecastle Stadium|Tynecastle]] in which he opened the scoring.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/4748451.stm |title=Hearts 4\u20130 Hibernian |date=7 August 2005 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 March 2008}}</ref> This was to be a common sight for the Hearts fans as Sk\u00e1cel went on to score 16 goals over the season and also scored the Hearts goal in the [[Scottish Cup]] final victory over Gretna.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/4764967.stm |title=Hearts 1\u20131 Gretna (4\u20132 on pens) |date=13 May 2006 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 March 2008}}</ref> He was shortlisted for the [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year|Scottish PFA Players' Player award]], but lost out [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] winger [[Shaun Maloney]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4951722.stm | title=Maloney in historic awards double | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=1 May 2006 | accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite announcing that the club had signed Sk\u00e1cel on a permanent deal,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/heart_of_midlothian/4960778.stm |title=Hearts say Skacel is staying on |date=2 May 2006 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 March 2008}}</ref> Sk\u00e1cel's celebration and post match comments after the Cup Final suggested that he had played his last game for the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/heart_of_midlothian/4770601.stm |title=Skacel bids farewell |date=14 May 2006 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 March 2008}}</ref> On 3 July 2006, it was revealed that Sk\u00e1cel and [[Andy Webster (footballer, born 1982)|Andy Webster]] had failed to join up with the squad for pre-season training prompting rumours of Sk\u00e1cel's departure.\n\nOpposition fans point to accusations of [[Diving (association football)|diving]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/heart_of_midlothian/4861978.stm |title=Skacel ready to alter behaviour |date=30 March 2006 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 March 2008}}</ref> and that he spat at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] captain [[Neil Lennon]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/heart_of_midlothian/4962096.stm |title=Lennon and Skacel row over spit |date=1 May 2006 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 March 2008}}</ref> although these accusations were reported to the [[Scottish Football Association]] they were not pursued.\n\n===Southampton and Hertha Berlin===\nOn 29 July 2006, Sk\u00e1cel joined [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for \u00a31.6 million<ref>{{cite web|title=Saints land Skacel in \u00a31.6m deal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/southampton/5227082.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=25 October 2010|date=29 July 2006}}</ref> and linked up again with former Hearts manager [[George Burley]]. Although Sk\u00e1cel plays in midfield he found himself playing the majority of games at left back after the departure of [[Gareth Bale]] to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in May 2007. He scored from 25 yards in the 3\u20132 victory of [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 6 October 2007.\n\nOn 31 January 2008, Sk\u00e1cel moved to [[Hertha BSC]] on loan until the end of the season. Sk\u00e1cel had requested the move to boost his chances of representing his country on the international scene. Southampton acting chief executive Lee Hoos was quoted as saying: \"The Czech national manager views the Championship very much as a second tier league \u2013 even though it is the fifth most popular in Europe. Sk\u00e1cel felt he would not get a look in unless he was playing in a top division\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11688/3097562/skacel-departs-southampton|title=Skacel departs Southampton|date= 1 February 2008|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> Sk\u00e1cel succeeded in making the [[UEFA Euro 2008]] squad, due to injury to [[Daniel Pudil]], but was an unused substitute in all three of their games as the Czechs crashed out at the group stages.\n\nSk\u00e1cel returned to Southampton for the start of the [[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309 season]]. He was released from his contract on 2 May 2009, after Southampton were relegated to League One.\n\n===Return to Slavia Prague===\nSk\u00e1cel returned to former club [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]] in October 2009, six years after leaving to join [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.transfermarketweb.com/?action=read&idsel=45930 | title = Skacel returns to Slavia | publisher = FOOTBALLpress.net | date = 13 October 2009 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> He made his first appearance since returning in a 2\u20131 league defeat to [[Sigma Olomouc]] at the [[Synot Tip Arena]].<ref>[http://www.slavia.cz/novinka.asp?id=16111&typ=clanek Slavia 1\u20132 Sigma] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206025321/http://www.slavia.cz/novinka.asp?id=16111 |date=6 February 2010 }}, Slavia.cz, 26 October 2009.</ref> He made his fifth and final league appearance of his second spell with the club on 29 November 2009, scoring a hat-trick against [[FC Brno]] in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1141563.html | title = Skacel treble downs Brno | publisher =  FIFA.com | date = 29 November 2009 | accessdate =24 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Larissa===\nIn January 2010, Sk\u00e1cel signed for Larissa on a free transfer until June 2010 with the option of a further year.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.soccerbase.gr/news.aspx?lang=en&id=2010-01-25 | title = Larissa signed Skacel | publisher = soccerbase.gr | accessdate =27 January 2010 | date = 25 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Heart of Midlothian===\nOn 16 September 2010, Sk\u00e1cel returned to Hearts on a one-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rudi returns to Hearts|url=http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20100916/rudi-returns-to-hearts_2241384_2141199|publisher=Hearts of Midlothian FC|accessdate=16 September 2010|date=16 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918210335/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20100916/rudi-returns-to-hearts_2241384_2141199|archivedate=18 September 2010}}</ref> He marked his first start and home debut in his second spell at Hearts with a goal against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].\n\nOn 23 October 2010, he bagged a hat-trick in Hearts' 3\u20130 win over [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jim Jefferies delighted by Hearts display |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/heart_of_midlothian/9121349.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=25 October 2010|date=23 October 2010}}</ref> Sk\u00e1cel continued his superb form with a 32nd-minute 30-yard volley against [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]] on 20 November 2010. Hearts went on to win the match 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hearts boss Jim Jefferies hails clinical finishing|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/heart_of_midlothian/9213071.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=22 November 2010|date=20 November 2010}}</ref> On 11 December 2010 he played a key role as the Jambos' recorded their biggest win of the season, scoring twice in a 5\u20130 victory over [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] at Tynecastle.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/9274624.stm | title = Hearts 5 \u2013 0 Aberdeen | publisher =  BBC Sport | date = 11 December 2010 | accessdate =16 December 2010}}</ref> On 19 March 2011 Sk\u00e1cel scored his 10th and 11th goals of the season in a dramatic 3\u20132 victory over [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]; his 93rd-minute strike proving the winner. Sk\u00e1cel ended the [[2010\u201311 Scottish Premier League|2010\u201311 season]] as the ''Jambos''' top scorer with 13 goals.\n\nDespite joining the Hearts squad for their pre-season preparations Sk\u00e1cel's involvement was severely limited due to injury. On 4 August, Hearts announced that Sk\u00e1cel had signed a new contract which would keep him at [[Tynecastle F.C.|Tynecastle]] until 31 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20110804/rudis-new-deal_2241384_2397110 | title = Rudi's new deal | publisher = Heartsfc.co.uk | date = 4 August 2011 | accessdate = 26 October 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20120802180849/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20110804/rudis-new-deal_2241384_2397110 | archivedate = 2 August 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> On the same day, in his second appearance of the season and first since signing a new deal, Sk\u00e1cel came off the bench to score his first goal of the season in the second leg of [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League#Third qualifying round|UEFA Europa League Third qualifying round]] against [[Paks]] in a 4\u20131 victory which got [[Paulo S\u00e9rgio Bento Brito|Paulo S\u00e9rgio]] off to winning start as manager.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20110804/match-report-hearts-4-1-paks-se_2241384_2410207 | title = Match Report: Hearts 4\u20131 Paks SE | publisher = Heartsfc.co.uk | date = 4 August 2011 | accessdate = 26 October 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20120802045601/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20110804/match-report-hearts-4-1-paks-se_2241384_2410207 | archivedate = 2 August 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Sk\u00e1cel's first six appearances of the season were as a substitute as he gradually regained fitness following a lack of pre-season action and his first [[2011\u201312 Scottish Premier League|SPL]] start did not come until 2 October 2011, a match in which he opened the scoring as the ''Jambos'' defeated [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] 2\u20130 at home.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15051297.stm | title = Hearts 2\u20130 Celtic | publisher = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 2 October 2011 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> He maintained his place in the starting line-up for the following game and scored again in a 2\u20130 win over [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline]] at [[East End Park]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15226141.stm | title = Dunfermline 0\u20132 Hearts | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 15 October 2011 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> He entered the final month of his contract in January 2012 and started the [[New Year]] in style as he scored the third goal as Hearts defeated [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibs]] 3\u20131 at [[Easter Road]] in the [[Edinburgh derby#New Year derby|New Year Edinburgh Derby]] on 2 January.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/16330946.stm | title = Hibernian 1\u20133 Hearts | publisher =  BBC Sport| date = 2 January 2012 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> He continued his impressive start to 2012 with his second Hearts hat-trick against St. Mirren at Tynecastle on 14 January. Following [[Marius \u017dali\u016bkas]]' [[Misconduct (association football)#Sending-off offences red card|sending-off]] the ''Jambos'' trailed 2\u20131 but Sk\u00e1cel's hat-trick inspired the ten men to an incredible 5\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/16453455.stm | title = Hearts 5\u20132 St. Mirren | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 14 January 2011 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> After the match Sk\u00e1cel, voiced his desire to extend his contract and spend the remainder of the season with Hearts.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16563619.stm | title = Hearts' Rudi Skacel wants to stay until the summer | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 14 January 2012 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> On 31 January 2012, Hearts announced that he had signed a contract extension and would be staying on until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20120131/rudi-staying-on_2241384_2591147 | title = Rudi staying on! | publisher = Heartsfc.co.uk | date = 31 January 2012 | accessdate = 26 October 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120203052506/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20120131/rudi-staying-on_2241384_2591147 | archivedate = 3 February 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> His 100th competitive appearance for Hearts came in a 2\u20130 [[Edinburgh derby]] win on 18 April 2012.  He continued his impressive goal scoring record against St. Mirren in the [[2011\u201312 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]], scoring in the quarter-finals in a 2\u20132 draw at Tynecastle,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17243643 | title = Hearts 2\u20132 St. Mirren | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 10 March 2012 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> as well as in a 2\u20130 victory at [[St Mirren Park]] in the resultant replay.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17363148 | title = St. Mirren 0\u20132 Hearts | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 21 March 2012 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> He also scored the opener in the [[2011\u201312 Scottish Cup#Semi-finals|semi-final]] victory over [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] at [[Hampden Park|Hampden]] as Hearts progressed to the final.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17649430 | title = Celtic 1\u20132 Hearts | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 15 April 2012 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> He scored the second and fifth goals and earned the [[man of the match]] award<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=1957&newsCategoryID=7&newsID=9890 | title = Skacel named man of the match | publisher = Scottish FA | date = 19 May 2012 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> as Hearts routed rivals [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibs]] 5\u20131 in a historic [[2012 Scottish Cup Final|final]], taking his goal tally in the competition to five in just seven games and 18 in all competitions for the season, his best return in his three seasons as a Hearts player. He said after the match that the final would probably be his last match for Hearts and that it was ''\"the best way to say goodbye with the cup in my hands\"'',<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18134313 | title = Scottish Cup hero Rudi Skacel 'likely to exit Hearts' | publisher = BBC Sport | date =  19 May 2012| accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> meaning that he would once again depart following a Scottish Cup triumph.\n\nOn 9 October 2012, Hearts announced that Sk\u00e1cel had returned to train with the club.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20121009/rudi-offered-training-facilities_2241384_2943993 | title = Rudi offered training facilities | publisher = Heartsfc.co.uk | date = 9 October 2012 | accessdate = 27 October 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121125061731/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20121009/rudi-offered-training-facilities_2241384_2943993 | archivedate = 25 November 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> However, a permanent return was made impossible by a transfer embargo imposed on the club by the SPL due to recurring late payments of the wages of players and staff.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/176087.html | title = SPL confirm Hearts transfer embargo | publisher = ESPN | date =  24 October 2012| accessdate = 27 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Dundee United===\nSkacel joined [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on 26 October 2012 contracted until 30 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/index.asp?tm=2&nid=4346&cd=2012 | title = United Sign Skacel | publisher = Dundee United | date = 26 October 2012 | accessdate = 26 October 2012}}</ref> He instantly caused controversy by, as he had previously hinted on his [[Twitter]] account, selecting the number 51 shirt at his new club in reference to Hearts' victory over rivals Hibernian in the [[2012 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup Final]]. Manager [[Peter Houston]] apologised to Hibs fans saying he was unaware of the significance of the number and would not have allowed Sk\u00e1cel to wear 51 had he known his reasons for selecting it.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11794/8199664/Dundee-United-boss-sorry-for-Rudi-Skacel-s-Hibs-wind-up | title = Dundee United boss sorry for Rudi Skacel's Hibs wind-up | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 27 October 2012 | accessdate = 27 October 2012}}</ref> Sk\u00e1cel made his debut a day after signing, as a second-half substitute in a 1\u20130 victory over [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] at [[St Mirren Park]]. He faced his former club, Hearts, four days later on 31 October in a [[2011-12 Scottish League Cup#Quarter-finals|Scottish League Cup quarter-final]] at [[Tannadice]] and received a warm reception from the travelling Hearts support when he appeared as a substitute in [[extra time#Association football|extra time]] as United were eventually defeated 5\u20134 on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20053644 | title = Dundee Utd 1\u20131 Hearts (4\u20135 pens) | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 31 October 2012 | accessdate = 2 December 2012}}</ref> His first seven appearances for Dundee United were as a substitute, before making his first start on 27 November 2012 in a 2\u20131 home defeat to [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] in the league. This match also marked his 100th appearance in the [[Scottish Premier League]]. He scored his first goal for the ''Terrors'' on 15 December 2012, in a thrilling 4\u20134 league draw with [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] at Tannadice.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20650417 | title = Dundee Utd 4\u20134 Inverness CT | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 15 December 2012 | accessdate = 17 December 2012}}</ref> He made a total of 16 appearances for United, scoring once as he was utilized primarily as a second-half substitute with ten of his appearances coming from the bench.\n\nOn 25 January 2013, Dundee United confirmed that they would not be extending Sk\u00e1cel's contract beyond January.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rudi Skacel set for Dundee United departure|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21200303|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 March 2013|date=25 January 2013}}</ref> Skacel left the club when his contract expired on 30 January.\n\n===Second return to Slavia Prague===\nOn 6 March 2013, [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]] announced that Sk\u00e1cel had returned for a third spell and signed a contract until the end of the season as the club battled against relegation.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sport.stv.tv/football/216579-rudi-skacel-rejoins-slavia-prague-until-the-end-of-the-season/ | title = Rudolf Sk\u00e1cel returns to Slavia Prague | publisher = STV | date = 6 March 2013 | accessdate = 6 March 2013}}</ref> He made the first appearance of his return on 16 March 2013 in a 3\u20131 [[2012\u201313 Gambrinus liga|league]] win over [[Slovan Liberec]] at [[Stadion Eden]], receiving a warm reception from the home fans as he came on as a substitute in the 69th minute. He replaced [[Captain (association football)|captain]] [[Karol Kisel]] and was given the captain's armband for the remainder of the game.\n\nHe departed upon the expiration of his contract at the end of the season having made a total of five appearances.\n\n===Later career===\nIn January 2014 Sk\u00e1cel was linked with a move to [[Scottish Championship]] side [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] where former Hearts teammate [[Paul Hartley]] was manager.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alloa eye Rudi Skacel after landing Hibs' Ross Caldwell |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25683935|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 February 2014|date=10 January 2014}}</ref>\nHowever The Wasps tentative interest went no further and days later it was revealed Sk\u00e1cel was once again training with Hearts with a view to signing for the administration hit club should the [[Scottish Professional Football League|SPFL]] allow for players made redundant in the summer to be replaced despite the club's transfer embargo.<ref>{{cite web|title=No immediate new faces at Hearts but Skacel in training|url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/no-immediate-new-faces-at-hearts-but-skacel-in-training-1-3267417|publisher=Edinburgh Evening News|accessdate=6 February 2014|date=14 January 2014}}</ref> Hearts cancelled the playing contract of goalkeeping coach [[Alan Combe]], in keeping with the one-in, one-out policy of their transfer embargo, to make space for Sk\u00e1cel<ref>{{cite web|title=Hearts seek under-21 recruit after Adam King's Swansea move|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25914429|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 February 2014|date=28 January 2014}}</ref> only for the SPFL to reject the move stating that it was not viable to replace a 39-year-old goalkeeping coach/player who has never appeared in a match day squad with a midfielder.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary snaps up striker|url=http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20140130/gary-snaps-up-striker_2241384_3645612|publisher=Heartsfc.co.uk|accessdate=6 February 2014|date=30 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202150935/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20140130/gary-snaps-up-striker_2241384_3645612|archivedate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Sk\u00e1cel expressed his bitter disappointment at the refusal and stated that the decision had left him without motivation and considering retirement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rudi Skacel: SPFL decision to block my Hearts move stinks |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/rudi-skacel-spfl-decision-to-block-my-hearts-move-stinks-1-3294669|publisher=Edinburgh Evening News|accessdate=6 February 2014|date=5 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Raith Rovers===\nAfter a spell in his native Czech Republic, Sk\u00e1cel was linked with a return to [[Scotland]], after [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] manager [[Gary Locke (Scottish footballer)|Gary Locke]] expressed an interest in the former [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech international]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/sport/football/scottish-championship/223601/raith-boss-gary-locke-makes-bid-to-bring-rudi-skacel-to-starks-park/ |title=Raith boss Gary Locke makes bid to bring Rudi Skacel to Stark\u2019s Park |first=Neil |last=Robertson |work=The Courier |publisher=DC Thomson Co Ltd |date=15 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> On 21 July 2016, Sk\u00e1cel signed with the [[Scottish Championship]] side.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raithrovers.net/25903/major-signing-news-skacel-and-mcmanus-join-lockes-rovers.htm |title=Major signing news: Skacel and McManus join Locke's Rovers |publisher=Raith Rovers F.C. |date=21 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 1. FK P\u0159\u00edbram ===\nFollowing his release from Raith Rovers, Skacel returned to the Czech Republic and signed for [[1. FK P\u0159\u00edbram]] in the Czech National Football League. In his first season with P\u0159\u00edbram he helped the club achieve promotion to the Czech First League. In his final playing season, Skacel made 16 appearances and scored one goal as P\u0159\u00edbram escaped relegation <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fkpribram.cz/clanek.asp?id=Rudolf-Skacel-v-nedeli-ukonci-karieru-5708|title=Rudolf Sk\u00e1cel v ned\u011bli ukon\u010d\u00ed kari\u00e9ru|website=1.FK P\u0158\u00cdBRAM - Fotbalov\u00fd klub|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fkpribram.cz/clanek.asp?id=Tohle-je-posledni-sezona-5475|title=Tohle je posledn\u00ed sezona|website=1.FK P\u0158\u00cdBRAM - Fotbalov\u00fd klub|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nSkacel retired following P\u0159\u00edbram's relegation playoff victory over [[FC Zbrojovka Brno]] on 2 June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fnliga.cz/clanek/4671-brno-v-pribrami-neskorovalo-a-po-bezbrankove-remize-se-udrzeli-stredocesi|title=Brno v P\u0159\u00edbrami nesk\u00f3rovalo a po bezbrankov\u00e9 rem\u00edze se udr\u017eeli St\u0159edo\u010de\u0161i|website=FORTUNA:N\u00c1RODN\u00cd LIGA|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/latest-hearts-news/rudi-skacel-hearts-legend-to-bring-curtain-down-on-career-this-weekend-1-4939346|title=Rudi Skacel, Hearts legend, to bring curtain down on career this weekend|website=www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nSk\u00e1cel made his [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic under-21]] debut against [[Bulgaria national under-21 football team|Bulgaria]] on 5 October 2001 in [[Teplice]], scoring the third goal in an 8\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fotbal.cz/c/nat/21/2001/match10.asp | title = Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 74 | language = Czech | publisher = fotbal.cz | accessdate = 16 October 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110811115329/http://www.fotbal.cz/c/nat/21/2001/match10.asp | archivedate = 11 August 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He was part of the [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic under-21]] [[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship squads#Czech Republic|squad]] at the [[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]] in [[Switzerland]], along with his future [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] teammate [[Michal Posp\u00ed\u0161il]]. Both players converted in a penalty shoot-out as the Czechs emerged victorious in the [[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship#Final|final]] against [[France under-21 national football team|France]].\n\nSk\u00e1cel made his [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic national team]] debut on 12 November 2003 against [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]. He once again got off to a scoring start as he replaced [[Jan Koller]] after 73 minutes and scored eight minutes later in a 5\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fotbal.cz/c/nat/AM/2003/match9.asp | title = Z\u00e1pis o utk\u00e1n\u00ed \u010d. 620/112 | language = Czech | publisher = fotbal.cz | accessdate = 16 October 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120503194426/http://www.fotbal.cz/c/nat/AM/2003/match9.asp | archivedate = 3 May 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He was named in the Czech squad for [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]] as a replacement for the injured [[Daniel Pudil]] but did not leave the bench as the Czechs exited at the group stage. Sk\u00e1cel amassed seven caps for his country, scoring once.\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/rudolf-skacel/1534/|title=Czech Republic - R. Skacel - Profile with news, career statistics and history - Soccerway|website=int.soccerway.com|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref>===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<ref>Including appearances in European competition, Scottish Challenge Cup and Scottish Relegation playoffs. </ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]]\n|[[2001\u201302 Gambrinus liga|2001\u201302]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Gambrinus liga]]\n|12||3||-||-||-||-||-||-||12||3\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 Gambrinus liga|2002\u201303]]\n|30||8||-||-||-||-||-||-||30||8\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 Gambrinus liga|2003\u201304]]\n|15||2||-||-||-||-||-||-||15||2\n|-\n|[[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]\n|[[2003\u201304 Ligue 1|2003\u201304]]\n|[[Ligue 1]]\n|20||1||2||0||2||0||0||0||24||1\n|-\n|[[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] (loan)\n|[[2004\u201305 Alpha Ethniki|2004\u201305]]\n|[[Alpha Ethniki]]\n|16||1||4||3||-||-||6||1||26||5\n|-\n|[[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] (loan)\n|[[2005\u201306 Scottish Premier League|2005\u201306]]\n|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|35||16||4||1||1||0||-||-||40||17\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n|[[2006\u201307 Football League Championship|2006\u201307]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Football League Championship]]\n|39||3||0||0||2||1||-||-||41||4\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Football League Championship|2007\u201308]]\n|16||1||1||0||1||0||-||-||18||1\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Football League Championship|2008\u201309]]\n|28||1||1||0||0||0||-||-||29||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|83||5||2||0||3||1||0||0||88||6\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Hertha BSC]] (loan)\n|[[2007\u201308 Bundesliga|2007\u201308]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Bundesliga]]\n|16||2||0||0||-||-||-||-||16||2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Gambrinus liga|2009\u201310]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Gambrinus Liga|Gambrinus liga]]\n|5||3||2||0||-||-||0||0||7||3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[AEL 1964 FC|Larissa]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Superleague Greece|2009\u201310]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Superleague Greece]]\n|7||0||0||0||-||-||0||0||7||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Scottish Premier League|2010\u201311]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|29||13||0||0||0||0||-||-||29||13\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Scottish Premier League|2011\u201312]]\n|29||12||7||5||1||0||3||1||40||18\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n|[[2012\u201313 Scottish Premier League|2012\u201313]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|14||1||1||0||1||0||0||0||16||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]]\n|[[2012\u201313 Gambrinus liga|2012\u201313]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Czech First League]]\n|5||0||0||0||-||-|| colspan=\"2\" |-||5||0\n|-\n|[[FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Czech First League|2015-16]]\n|[[Czech First League]]\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n| colspan=\"2\" | -\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Raith Rovers F.C. season|2016-17]]\n|[[Scottish Championship]]\n|24\n|0\n|2\n|0\n|1\n|0\n|2\n|0\n|25\n|0\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[1. FK P\u0159\u00edbram]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Czech National Football League|2017-18]]\n|[[Czech National Football League]]\n|27\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n| colspan=\"2\" | -\n|27\n|4\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Czech First League|2018-19]]\n|[[Czech First League]]\n|16\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|16\n|1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Hearts total\n|93||41||11||6||2||0||3||1||109||48\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Slavia Prague total\n|67||16||2||0||0||0||0||0||69||16\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!435!!72!!24!!9!!9!!1!!11!!2!!479!!84\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!National team||Club||Season||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]\n|2003